What is Right paradigm in C++?

“Right paradigm” in C++ is the wrong way to think about it. 
C++ is designed so you choose the paradigm that best fits the problem, often mixing several in one program.

Let’s make it practical.

Main paradigms in C++

1. Procedural (C-style)

Functions + simple data
Good for:
Small programs
Embedded / low-level code
Performance-critical tight loops
int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }

👉 Use when logic is simple and structure doesn’t matter much.

2. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

Classes, encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism
class Sensor {
public:
    virtual void read() = 0;
};

👉 Good for:

Large systems
Modeling real-world entities
UI frameworks (like Qt)

⚠️ Don’t overuse inheritance—modern C++ prefers composition.

3. Generic Programming (Templates)

Write code once, works for many types
template<typename T>
T max(T a, T b) { return a > b ? a : b; }

👉 Good for:

Libraries
Reusable components
STL-style design
4. Functional Style (Modern C++)
Lambdas, immutability, algorithms
std::for_each(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int x) {
    std::cout << x << "\n";
});

👉 Good for:

Cleaner, declarative code
Working with containers
⚖️ So which is “right”?
✅ Real answer:

Use a combination, not a single paradigm.

    🧩 Practical guideline (very important)
    🔹 Use OOP for structure
        Controllers, models (like your Qt work)
        Clear ownership and responsibilities
    🔹 Use generic programming for reuse
        Utilities
        Data structures
        Templates instead of copy-paste
    🔹 Use functional style for operations
        Transforming data
        STL algorithms
        Lambdas for callbacks
    🔹 Use procedural for low-level parts
        Performance-critical code
        Simple logic
🚀 Recommended style (modern C++ mindset)

If you want a solid direction:

“OOP for architecture + templates for reuse + functional for operations”

This is how most modern C++ systems are written.

🔥 Example (mixed paradigm)
class Processor {
public:
    void process(std::vector<int>& data) {
        std::for_each(data.begin(), data.end(), [](int& x) {
            x *= 2;  // functional style
        });
    }
};

Class → OOP
std::vector → generic
lambda → functional

👉 This is idiomatic modern C++

🧠 Important mindset

Don’t try to force C++ into:

“pure OOP” (like Java) ❌
“pure functional” ❌

C++ is about:

using the right tool at the right place

🎯 For your case (Qt + C++ backend)

Based on your work:

Use OOP → Controllers, Models
Use templates → reusable utilities / adaptors
Use functional → signals, lambdas, STL ops
Avoid heavy inheritance trees
